segments.text: Okay, just go right ahead.
So that's what we were thinking about on chemical characterization of it.
Then we felt that we needed to do some processing work.
One of the cries that has gone up previously is, well, you remember two, three years ago we had this small seeded grain in the high plains.
Well, that wouldn't process.
In other words, they'd try to run it through their steam flaking equipment, and then the regular grain would do all right, and that damn stuff wouldn't do.
So Dean Ray told me by phone that they had some loads of this stuff coming up there.
They were going to try it in processing, and if it would work, well, they'd try to work it into their rations.
If it wouldn't, well, they'd just be hands off of it.

So we thought we'd better do some processing work on it to see what would happen to this type of material when it is processed by the usual methods, dry grinding, micronizing, steam flaking, and then, of course, the wet grain treatment reconstitution, this type of thing.
Then, too, we felt that we should do digestion work with it

And this is where Lichtenwalder is going to come in and then do animal studies which would involve growth and lactation and those two mainly using dairy cattle and swine and poultry and beef cattle and Lichtenwalder I think will probably feed it to some lambs as well.
So that's where we are on it and of course this jar, I mean
Dudley Smith sat through this meeting with us, and he sort of provided the administrative blessing, I guess, for it.
And it's gone from there to where this has now been sent out to department heads and resident directors.
We're apparently in business.
Could I get a copy of that?
Yeah, I haven't got anybody to copy it today.
The secretary's gone, we've got to get this killed.
It's got some terminology in there I think that might be helpful to us.
Thank you.
John, I believe that Dudley told me that I believe this was a group, sort of the initial task force that went down there that included Roland Smith, the extension grain marketing specialist.
And what does this mean on fulfilling a grain contract?
I assume this is one of the real concerns.
That's it.

Right after we were down there, there was a representative of a Japanese company in here, and I asked him what they were, he had spent some time looking at the situation, and he said, well, our contracts call for number two grain, and we can get plenty of it elsewhere.
And you see, the interesting thing was,
If you go down to the lower valley, they started earlier, and they're harvesting down there, and they might have had 75% of it out before the rain hit.
So the grain, so the harvest was progressing northward until it was stopped by this heavy rain at Corpus Christi in that area.
And at that point, Norman Vestal, agent in Oasis County, said, we got a wall-to-wall grain sorghum in this county that's probably in the neighborhood of 300,000 acres.
And there's over 200,000 of it that's still in the field.
So they had, we'll say maybe 20-25% of their harvested up there.
In previous years when this had happened, they only had a limited amount of this stuff.
And they could blend it with their already harvested better grain and go ahead and send it for export.
Well, this year, when you got 75% of it like this, you ain't got nothing to blend to it.
That's right.
So there they sit with all this grain.
They've either got to bring in grain from outside the area to blend with it or else do something else with it.
And plus the fact that it was probably in worse condition than previously been the case, too.
Well, now, on your designated task force for the Sargon Research, how
Do you continue to work with Extension?
Or do you?
There's no one on that list from the director's office.
That's right.
That was sort of an enabling act, wasn't it?
Yes, it was sort of an enabling act.
Well, first off, we called on the Extension people, Robert Rupp, area livestock specialist, and the district agent, Lynn Wilson,
down there to can you find us some grain that is one hybrid part of which has been harvested before and part of which has been harvested after this weather period.
They did a lot of looking and they never did come up with any really.
Now apparently Prairie Foundation had some of their own that they had done this with and they are running a test with
In other words, I'm including them right in the thing just like they belong to the outfit.
I don't see any reason not to.
And we may have the opportunity to do this with King Ranch also since they grew a lot of grain and they still have a lot in the field.
And Steven Clayberg and some others were here last Monday.
You were doubtless at that luncheon.
He said that, well, who knows, we might have a hurricane that'll
do the same thing to some grain that isn't already harvested.
And if it happens, well, we'll be happy to work with you on this any way we can.
But meantime, though, we've got Lucas Reyes.
And Lucas is the agronomist.
He's doing such things as the date of planting studies and the hybrid and variety tests.
And he has provided us, from his data planting work, 24 samples of grain that run from 11 to about 20 pounds, 12 of which were harvested before the rain and 12 of which were harvested afterwards.
Now these would be the same variety.
The early planting in February was harvested before the rain.
That that was planted in, I think, about the first of April.
was harvested after the rain, but it's the same variety, so we get the varietal difference out here, hopefully.
We got 53 samples from the outfit down there at Corpus.
Whoever and wherever and all they came from, I'm not sure.
But at any rate, we've got them and they're identified, and there are quantities of those that will be enough to let us do everything except
the digestibility in the animal studies.
We think with these samples from Lucas Reyes, there will be enough to do some chick studies, baby chick, which will be a good thing.
On that 53 now, if you don't have a control, John, how can you really assess?
Well, what we think of in connection with those is, okay, we can look at them chemically, we can look at them microbiologically,
and tell what we've got here.
And of course, a lot of this is going to have to be compared on the historical experience.
In other words, I think Pettit
The group over there, they've been doing this sort of thing.
They know pretty well what to expect in normal grain.
And they're on top of this whole business of mycotoxins and amplitoxins and so on.
So I think that's why we just simply call it microbiological characterization.
Yeah, they'll look at, the plan is at least, that they will look at everything we've got.
If we've got it before and after, why...
So much the better.
I'm not sure what we'll get out of the 53 varieties, frankly, except maybe a body of information.
An assessment of what is coming in.
Okay, there it is.
What does it analyze?
And there are some notes made about the dates that the things were taken and this sort of thing.
And you can tell pretty much what it looks like.
But I think the simple fact that they'll be taking grain like that and plating it out
to get an idea of what's going to grow off of it.
And that will be useful information.
Now all of this we're thinking of is pretty short term stuff.
In other words, what I'm shooting for is to have a package of information that we can pretty much put together and make a publishable document of some kind by about Christmas.
So we're not talking about years on this thing.
We're talking about trying to hit it pretty hard.
And I don't think very many of the things that we are talking about doing will take very much time.
We're talking about only an 84 day feeding period on the cattle.
Well, September, October, November.
That'll do it.
We can get them started with the first of September.
And producers, meantime, they just have store grain.
And then if we get an assessment that it
really hasn't injured feeding value all that much, then we can move it into even the international markets, or certainly international markets.
Now, of course, you're going to have to convince people of this, and this is the whole idea of trying to develop and document some definite information.
Up to now, we really don't have that much information about it.
I think everybody knows about it.

The Prairie Foundation did a little feeding study the last time we had this, and their story was that this, what they called black grain, they didn't get a grade under anything then, was just as good as far as cattle performance is concerned as their better number two grain was.
This grain sardine that you spoke of that had lodged completely, is that pretty much like corn?
Will it pick itself up again?
Yeah, by the time we got down there to Beeville this last time, Corpus, we went by there and it was harvested.
It was gone.
And Tom Longnecker told us that, well they didn't have a place to store it or anything and it was all damaged.
He said we sent it all over to Perry Foundation because we had a bunch of our own cattle over there anyway.
and therefore we sent it over there.
Did they have to have any special pickup equipment or was it just a conventional combine?
I didn't ask you.
A lot of times when something like soybeans lodge, you have to have a special pickup arms.
Yes, this is true I think with nearly anything that they harvest that way, with binders and mowers and combines and the whole works.
But that's sort of where we are.
We're in the process now of trying to, well, we've got these samples, nearly 100 of them, 53 plus 24, and I know there's some more.
We've got some from Prairie Foundation, and I don't know, I mean, Lake Mauna has got all of those.
But we're looking at almost 100 samples of grain already.
There's a lot of these things that we can do without any further ado.
Just get at it.
And the best judgment is that you've got something in excess of a half million acres involved.
That's right.
Now there's some terrific losses.
For example, Leo Welder at Refurio had just finished combine.
We visited him on this same trip to Beville.
had just finished combining, and he said that before the rain, they were harvesting something like 42, 4300 pounds an acre.
After the rain, they were cutting about 26.
Almost half of it.
Yeah, in other words, and you don't see it so much now, but when they first brought this back and they first began to get dry, he'd shake them like that and they'd just shower out of there.
All the loose stuff is gone now pretty well, but it doesn't take too much.
You can get grain out of it still, so there's an awful lot.
They said that they probably had the biggest acreage and the highest yield they've ever had.
But the grain market has been real funny.
At the right after that, in other words during the week of wet weather after we were down there with this crash meeting,
grain sorghum was selling at Corpus at about $4.85, $4.90.
And then there was a boy in here in my office from Dilley, which is down there by Cotulla, that way.
And I don't know whether the boy was completely knowledgeable or not, but he said they were paying five and a quarter farmers for grain at Dilley.
John McNeil was down here for the animal science meetings from Amarillo, an area extension man out there.
And he said the market had absolutely gone pot on the grain out there.
Those people out there are just not interested in the Danish grain at all.
I think probably because the grain had ripened farther north and began to get harvested here and on into central Texas.
In other words, the grain was moving.
They weren't out of grain out there anyway, so they began to take her off, and there's no support price on the grain anymore.
They better watch it that they don't crowd some of these South Texas cattlemen into moving into the feeding end of it and feed their own grain.
Could be.
If they haven't got any market for this sort of stuff, the old cattle in South Texas might win it pretty well.
That's right.
Sure might.
So, but that's sort of our story.
Well, that's great.
I hate stories about what we're going to do.
Well, I always say, John, that such a story on research is sort of like trying to sit on a two-legged stool.
We've got a problem and we're doing something about it, but we don't yet have a third leg with your research results.
Which will prop it up.
Yeah.
So...
Could I also get a copy of this U.S. Standard?
You can take that one.
That's the only one I've got.
I got it from Roland Smith.
I can give you another one.
All right.
I believe that would be helpful to fill in our knowledge to make sure we don't say something.
One of the things about processing, you don't know Charter Pierce in the micronizing process, do you?
Well, he invented, Chardo invented the micronizing process.
What is that?
Which consists, well it's a substitute for steam flaking.
Steam flaking is what's been accepted in the cattle feeding industry pretty well.
It's a pretty energy intensive system.
But Chardo started out to pop grain.
And he developed this machine.
It's nothing in the world except for
In other words, this is just a steel plate that runs through here with a flanged edge on it to keep the grain on.
And it oscillates anyways like this.
There's a motor that just simply runs.
Popcorn shaker.
Yeah, same idea as shaking it in a skillet.
And these infrared generators are lined up over the top of it here.
These are all gas.
It's gas-fired.
The grain goes in here, and it dribbles onto this skillet.
and passes under these infrared generators, and as it gets down to this end here, it pops like this.
What percentage of moisture does it have to be to pop successfully?
Well, that's part of this thing here.
And one thing is, it's like popcorn.
There's some of it that simply won't pop, except this is the much worse than any popcorn you ever saw.
There's no comparison.
We did have some information...

on the uh influence of moisture it is right here on percentage of pop and it looked as if it seems to be something like that and what if it doesn't pop well they do you can make another use of it i suppose well and what we found out from this was that it really doesn't need to pop anyway
Because in this right here, first thing we learned is that the darn stuff isn't all going to pop.
And therefore, to get any information on the influence of popped grain on animal performance, we're going to have to screen it so we have 100% popped.
So in this thing here, we put a screen right in there, quarter-inch mesh.
And that stuff that dropped through we called partial and non-popped.
And it went through a rotor mill and came out here.

that which came on over the screen was a hundred percent popped and it dropped in here and came out here and then we just plugged the thing up and let the whole mess come together through and we called that the uh partial and non-pop no the pop grain mixture yeah well the important thing is that we found that all of the heat treated grain

differed from the original grain, but these three fractions didn't differ from one another in anything we measured, which indicated pretty strongly that it wasn't popping, per se, that was doing the job.
It was the heat treatment.
On the basis of that, Chardo Pierce scrapped the idea of popping grain, and he went to the micronizing concept.
And what he's done now, instead of heating this to the popping stage like this,
he heats it to where there's only about one or two percent that'll pop right in here.
And all that is is a practical indicator that the grain is hot enough.
And from there then, he drops that hot grain into loosely set rolls, and you come out with this right here.
In other words, it's a kind of a thick, spongy kind of a thing.
it looks like it's almost been flexed yeah yeah but it's it's in strict contrast to steam flaking which is this stuff here in other words the steam flake is a wet process
